folder: Rutgers Street & Henry Street, Manhattan, NY
text:
(1)
Rutgers Street, west side, north from, but not including Henry, to
and including Canal Streets.
June 6. 1930.
P. L. Sperr.
(2)
The same, at a later date, showing the change in appearance of Nos. 10-18 Rutgers Street, the two 4-story buildings between Henry Street and East Broadway. On the extreme left, is a portion of St. Teresa's R.C. Church, located at the N.W. corner of Henry Street.
March 19. 1934.
P. L. Sperr.

folder: Henry Street & Rutgers Street, Manhattan, NY
text:
Henry Street, east from Rutgers Street, showing clearance at the N.E. corner, after demolition of the 6-story corner house No. 149-153. Also shown is the School for Crippled Children No. 155-159.(adjoining the clearance). In the far background is visible a portion of the Williamsburg
Bridge. On the left is the Rabbi Jacob Joseph School the empty area is where a park will be built dedicated to Captain Joseph who died fighting the Germans during WW2.
In the background to the left the back of the Forward building can also be seen!!
April 15, 1932.
P. L. Sperr.

folder: Rutgers Street & Henry Street, Manhattan, NY
text:
(1)
Rutgers Street, east side, between Henry Street and East Broadway,
showing the rears of buildings facing on East Broadway.
The empty lot is the future site of Captain Jacob Joseph memorial park!
March 39, 1934.
P. L. Sperr.
(2)
The same at an earlier date, showing the rear and side walls of the Jewish Daily Forward Building at 173175 East Broadway. (The Jewish Daily Forward
is an official organ of the Socialist Party of America).
April 5, 1932.
P. L. Sperr.
